WEBVTT

00:04.129 --> 00:06.756
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

00:09.009 --> 00:10.176
(CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKING)

00:15.515 --> 00:16.891
-ANDY: Good morning, John.
-JOHN: Morning.

00:17.600 --> 00:20.353
Uh, Edward Miller.
Georgia driver’s license.

00:20.437 --> 00:21.855
-Shot in the chest.
-Who found him?

00:21.938 --> 00:25.567
Manager. Door was open.
We’re about wrapped up here, actually.

00:25.692 --> 00:27.444
Seein' as we've already been here
for half an hour.

00:27.610 --> 00:28.903
-(CAMERA CLICKING)
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

00:29.029 --> 00:30.905
Do we know what the D.O.A.
was in town for?

00:30.989 --> 00:33.950
-BALDWIN: No, not yet.
-What, uh, you’re not bathing anymore?

00:35.410 --> 00:37.495
I ran out of razors.
Remind me to pick some up.

00:39.289 --> 00:42.000
Uh, there’s no forced entry.
D.O.A. had all his money on him.

00:42.459 --> 00:44.669
-GREG: Phone records?
-Manager’s faxing ’em to the squad.

00:44.753 --> 00:46.421
Uh, Rita and the new girl
are gonna run 'em.

00:46.880 --> 00:48.798
Okay. John says she seems real nice.

00:48.923 --> 00:50.383
You wore those same clothes yesterday.

00:50.592 --> 00:52.594
Actually I bought about
ten of this identical outfit.

00:52.886 --> 00:55.680
That way, each morning I don’t have to
waste time wondering what I’m gonna wear.

00:56.306 --> 00:59.726
I think I read Einstein
did that same thing.

01:00.018 --> 01:03.104
You hear that?
Einstein. Dude was a genius.

01:03.646 --> 01:05.482
Why don’t you guys
start knocking on doors, huh?

01:12.072 --> 01:13.698
So, uh, out all night again?

01:14.115 --> 01:18.036
-(SCOFFS) Which you’ve never done.
-Doesn’t suit you, John.

01:19.746 --> 01:22.749
(CLEARS THROAT) I got it handled.
Thanks, though.

01:32.842 --> 01:36.054
Laura Murphy. she transferred over
from applicant investigations.

01:36.262 --> 01:37.263
Andy Sipowicz.

01:37.347 --> 01:38.431
-Hey.
-Hi.

01:39.265 --> 01:42.769
Greg Medavoy. Baldwin Jones. John Clark.

01:43.019 --> 01:44.354
-How’s it going?
-LAURA: Great.

01:44.479 --> 01:45.855
Looking forward to working with you guys.

01:45.980 --> 01:47.107
Welcome on-board.

01:48.983 --> 01:51.694
-Thanks.
-(TELEPHONE RINGING)

01:53.363 --> 01:54.781
Came for you this morning.

01:55.740 --> 01:57.992
The D.O.A. was single, no kids.

01:58.284 --> 02:00.120
I talked to a neighbour of his
in Savannah.

02:00.328 --> 02:03.123
She said he’s a retired doctor,
came to New York to research a book.

02:03.665 --> 02:05.125
Anything on the hotel phone records?

02:05.416 --> 02:07.919
One call to and from
a Larry Pregitzer in Jersey City.

02:08.002 --> 02:09.003
He’s on his way in.

02:09.129 --> 02:11.923
So, you were a detective
in applicant investigations?

02:12.048 --> 02:13.049
Right.

02:13.174 --> 02:15.009
Doing background checks on people
who want to be cops?

02:15.885 --> 02:18.054
-Everybody rags on that unit.
-’Cause you don’t do

02:18.138 --> 02:20.306
any criminal investigations,
and you’re not on the street.

02:20.431 --> 02:22.642
I did three years in uniform
up at the seven-five,

02:22.809 --> 02:24.269
so don’t worry about me out on the street.

02:24.435 --> 02:27.397
Oh, don’t listen to him.
We’re glad to have you here, Laura.

02:27.856 --> 02:30.233
-(TELEPHONE RINGING)
-P.A.B. What does that mean? P.A.B.

02:30.400 --> 02:31.734
-No idea.
-RITA: We just got a call

02:31.818 --> 02:33.570
on a homeless D.O.A.
We’re gonna head down there now.

02:33.987 --> 02:35.905
Any word on when
the new lieutenant’s showing up?

02:36.156 --> 02:37.448
It’s supposed to be sometime today.

02:38.700 --> 02:39.951
What the hell is this?

02:40.118 --> 02:41.578
-(TELEPHONE RINGING)
-(POLICE SIREN WAILING)

02:41.744 --> 02:43.746
That’s a... that’s a dead rat, Andy.

02:43.913 --> 02:46.833
Yeah. Run this return address.
See if it even exists.

02:46.916 --> 02:48.793
You got this?
'Cause we need to head down there.

02:49.043 --> 02:50.920
Yeah, we’re covered.
Again, glad to have you here, Laura.

02:51.045 --> 02:52.505
Thanks.

02:52.714 --> 02:54.966
P.A.B. What the hell does that mean?

02:55.341 --> 02:57.343
-I don’t know.
-(TELEPHONE RINGING)

02:57.427 --> 02:59.929
-(CHUCKLES)
-This is funny to you?

03:00.263 --> 03:03.308
Yeah, come on, it’s probably a joke
by Tommy Doyle or one of the guys

03:03.391 --> 03:05.059
-you used to work with.
-(TELEPHONE RINGING)

03:14.444 --> 03:17.572
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

04:07.872 --> 04:11.584
(THEME MUSIC CONCLUDES)

04:24.138 --> 04:25.390
-Uh-oh!
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

04:25.598 --> 04:28.434
-They’ll let anybody in this place.
-What’s up, kid?

04:29.727 --> 04:32.438
-My partner, Rita Ortiz. this is Ted Kio.
-Hey.

04:32.605 --> 04:35.608
-Ted and I were at the academy together.
-So, detective in the squad, I hear.

04:35.733 --> 04:37.443
Yeah. (CHUCKLES) First day.

04:37.652 --> 04:39.529
How did you land a plumb job
like that so quick?

04:39.654 --> 04:42.573
My boss at applicant investigations,
he promised to fast-track me

04:42.657 --> 04:45.201
-if I gave him two years there.
-Luck of the Irish over here.

04:45.660 --> 04:48.913
-You handling this job?
-Yeah, D.O.A. is Sean O’Leary,

04:49.080 --> 04:50.832
shot three times
in the force of the chest.

04:50.915 --> 04:52.917
I’d seen him around,
had to roust him a couple times.

04:53.001 --> 04:54.752
Him and this other character
named King Tut.

04:54.877 --> 04:56.629
-(CAR HONKING)
-LAURA: Is that King Tut?

04:56.963 --> 05:00.008
-No, that’s road dog, aka Jason Keys.
-(DOG GROWLS)

05:00.091 --> 05:02.176
He found the D.O.A.,
then flagged down a radio car.

05:04.178 --> 05:07.348
-RITA: Uh, did you know the D.O.A.?
-Yeah, he was a real bro, too.

05:07.682 --> 05:09.559
-Did you see him last night?
-We were kicking it

05:09.642 --> 05:12.895
with these couple of squares.
They were on, like, this field-trip thing.

05:13.146 --> 05:15.690
They had money and all.
They were paying for stuff, so.

05:15.857 --> 05:16.858
Field-trip thing?

05:17.066 --> 05:21.237
Yes. Homeless Outreach Program,
Street Race.

05:21.571 --> 05:24.866
Something like that. I don’t know.
it was a guy and a girl, real squares.

05:25.074 --> 05:27.827
-D.O.A. have any beef with anyone?
-There’s always beefs out here.

05:28.036 --> 05:29.662
-Anything specific?
-No.

05:29.871 --> 05:32.498
He was a real bro, you know.
He shared what he had when he had it.

05:32.707 --> 05:34.667
-He had a street name?
-Yeah, The Illness.

05:35.168 --> 05:39.714
His name is Sean, then it was Chron,
then Chronic, then Chronic Illness,

05:40.465 --> 05:42.133
-then The Illness.
-Got it.

05:42.967 --> 05:45.011
If you could stick around a little bit,
we’d appreciate it.

05:45.803 --> 05:48.681
-We were gonna head to Frisco tomorrow.
-We’re really sorry.

05:49.891 --> 05:51.434
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

05:51.559 --> 05:54.687
Hey, this King Tut
the D.O.A. hung out with,

05:55.021 --> 05:56.314
think you can get your hands on him?

05:56.731 --> 05:59.692
-For you? Anything.
-Oh, you’re the best.

06:08.910 --> 06:10.286
(CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKING)

06:22.799 --> 06:24.175
Still can’t believe it happened.

06:24.425 --> 06:26.094
Yeah, I’m sure it was a bit of a shock.

06:26.427 --> 06:28.763
How long did you know
Dr. Miller, Mr. Pregitzer?

06:28.971 --> 06:31.724
Uh, he... he was our family doctor
many years ago,

06:31.849 --> 06:34.727
before he moved to Philadelphia,
and we stayed in touch since.

06:34.811 --> 06:36.020
Did you know he was in town?

06:36.396 --> 06:38.689
Yes, he called me from the hotel
he was staying at.

06:38.773 --> 06:40.316
JOHN: He mentioned
what he was doing in town?

06:40.775 --> 06:43.528
-Uh, sightseeing.
-He mentioned a book he was working on,

06:43.611 --> 06:45.238
maybe the... the subject matter?

06:45.947 --> 06:47.448
No, no, not to me.

06:47.824 --> 06:49.909
Did Ed talk about any problems
he was having out here

06:49.992 --> 06:50.993
or anything like that?

06:51.285 --> 06:55.123
He was single.
He... he never married. (SIGHS)

06:55.665 --> 06:58.501
-Yeah. Go ahead, Mr. Pregitzer.
-He told me last night

06:58.584 --> 07:02.255
that he met a woman in a bar,
and when they got back to his room,

07:02.380 --> 07:05.299
she wanTed money,
which was a shock to him

07:05.925 --> 07:09.053
and he told me that
she yelled at him for wasting her time

07:09.137 --> 07:10.596
and made a few threats and left.

07:10.930 --> 07:13.599
-He say which bar he met her?
-No, no, but... but I asked him

07:13.724 --> 07:14.725
how old she was, though.

07:14.934 --> 07:18.521
And he said she was in her thirties.
Well, I told him... (CHUCKLES)

07:18.896 --> 07:20.898
"Ed, you... you’re 70 years old.

07:21.441 --> 07:24.944
"Uh, no offense, but do you really think
a young woman is gonna go back

07:25.027 --> 07:28.197
"to your hotel and you had no idea
that she was a prostitute?"

07:28.322 --> 07:29.365
He claims he didn’t.

07:30.825 --> 07:33.119
He always had a bit of an ego, though.

07:33.411 --> 07:36.747
He mentioned anything else
in your conversation that might help us?

07:36.914 --> 07:40.251
No, but if I remember anything,
I’ll give you a call.

07:40.334 --> 07:42.253
All right. Thanks for coming in,
Mr. Pregitzer.

07:44.130 --> 07:45.298
(ANDY CLEARS THROAT)

07:46.382 --> 07:48.468
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER)
-(TELEPHONE RINGING)

07:51.053 --> 07:53.222
Hit up the night clerk again
at the D.O.A.’s hotel.

07:54.140 --> 07:56.267
See if he knows the names of the prosses
that work the place.

07:56.350 --> 07:58.311
-Sounds good.
-(LIQUID POURING)

07:58.478 --> 08:01.189
New lieutenant’s gonna be showing up soon.
I got a razor in my locker.

08:01.272 --> 08:02.523
You might think about shaving.

08:04.400 --> 08:06.569
Yeah, I’ll wait to see
if he has a problem with it.

08:08.571 --> 08:10.990
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER)
-(TELEPHONE RINGING)

08:11.157 --> 08:12.408
But you know who I’m talking about.

08:12.575 --> 08:16.871
Oh, yeah, yeah, uh, The Illness.
Yeah, his real name is Sean.

08:17.371 --> 08:18.831
Yeah, he’s a nice enough kid,

08:19.040 --> 08:21.083
but he’s a pain in the ass
when he gets drunk, though.

08:21.375 --> 08:24.378
-Did you see him last night?
-In the afternoon, not last night.

08:24.504 --> 08:27.340
-Anybody you know is after him?
-No, why should I tell you that?

08:27.590 --> 08:29.592
Oh, I don’t know, ’cause he’s dead?

08:29.759 --> 08:32.512
What you know how many times
I felt one of you all’s nightsticks

08:32.595 --> 08:35.515
in my ribs? I ain’t helping you people.

08:35.932 --> 08:37.934
King Tut. My partner, Rita Ortiz.

08:38.392 --> 08:41.437
Caught the King on a bad day here.
Says he doesn’t know anything.

08:41.646 --> 08:43.773
Well, witness said the D.O.A.
was hanging around two white kids

08:43.856 --> 08:47.360
on a field trip. Name of the organization
might have been Street Race.

08:47.443 --> 08:48.653
You heard of it?

08:49.737 --> 08:53.533
Oh, come on.
Don’t think of it as helping a cop,

08:53.866 --> 08:55.243
think of it as helping a friend.

08:55.451 --> 08:59.205
-I ain’t friends with nobody.
-You friends with 20 bucks?

08:59.497 --> 09:01.999
-(TELEPHONE RINGING)
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER OVER P.A.)

09:02.291 --> 09:05.044
Street Embrace. (CHUCKLES)
That’s what they call it.

09:05.253 --> 09:09.173
A bunch of guilty rich people
who pretend they homeless on the weekend.

09:09.257 --> 09:12.009
(LAUGHS) And they call me crazy.

09:12.760 --> 09:14.011
Is Street Embrace a local thing?

09:14.387 --> 09:18.015
Now, how in the hell would I know?
Look, are we through up in here?

09:18.266 --> 09:21.352
-’Cause I got places to be.
-Thanks for your help.

09:23.062 --> 09:26.232
-(TELEPHONE RINGING)
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER OVER P.A.)

09:26.607 --> 09:29.860
Hey, Ted. Keep an eye on King Tut,
will you?

09:30.403 --> 09:32.238
-You got it.
-Thanks.

09:34.740 --> 09:35.950
(SIGHS)

09:38.244 --> 09:40.288
This guy’s saying
it might have been a hooker involved.

09:40.496 --> 09:42.290
D.O.A.’s cellphone dump come back yet?

09:42.415 --> 09:44.875
Yeah, a couple calls to an Eric Pregitzer.

09:45.167 --> 09:46.836
How’s he relaTed to the guy
we just talked to?

09:46.961 --> 09:47.962
-The son.
-Hmm.

09:48.045 --> 09:49.046
He’s on his way in.

09:53.759 --> 09:57.013
Listen, if you, uh, if you have
any questions, feel free to ask.

09:57.096 --> 09:58.723
I’ll be happy to help any way I can.

09:58.973 --> 10:01.392
Thanks for offer.
I’m sure I’ll have a ton of questions.

10:01.809 --> 10:03.102
What made you wanna be a cop?

10:03.311 --> 10:04.520
I always wanted to be one,

10:04.729 --> 10:06.564
which didn’t make my dad
and my brothers too happy.

10:06.647 --> 10:08.357
Uh, they’re not big on you
being on the job?

10:08.733 --> 10:11.152
-They’re all firemen.
-Ay-ay-ay

10:11.652 --> 10:13.779
If you got a beef with firemen,
I don’t want to hear about it.

10:14.405 --> 10:16.574
Lieutenant Thomas Bale.
How’s everyone doing today?

10:16.907 --> 10:18.034
P.A.A. John Irvin.

10:18.159 --> 10:20.077
-Nice to meet you.
-Laura Murphy.

10:20.953 --> 10:24.040
-Rita Ortiz.
-Baldwin Jones.

10:24.415 --> 10:26.250
-Greg Medavoy.
-John Clark.

10:26.375 --> 10:28.336
-Andy Sipowicz.
-So, you’re Andy Sipowicz.

10:28.461 --> 10:30.171
-Yep.
-I heard a lot about you.

10:30.546 --> 10:33.049
I’ll need a few minutes to get settled in,
then you can catch me up

10:33.132 --> 10:34.467
on any cases you’re working.

10:34.592 --> 10:36.969
Later, I’ll conduct
individual orientation sessions.

10:37.053 --> 10:39.639
I’ve heard the name Bale
from internal affairs. You relaTed?

10:40.014 --> 10:43.059
That’s me.
I realize that carries a certain stigma,

10:43.392 --> 10:45.144
but I think you’ll find me
to be an excellent boss.

10:45.728 --> 10:48.314
(TELEPHONE RINGING)

10:54.403 --> 10:58.324
(SIGHS) Time to start covering your ass
would be right about now, guys.

11:14.048 --> 11:17.343
On the rat phone trading rat stories
with his rat buddies.

11:17.593 --> 11:20.054
Hey, let’s give him a chance, Andy.
He seems...

11:20.304 --> 11:21.305
The dead rat.

11:22.098 --> 11:24.475
Somebody must’ve known this guy
was gonna be our lieutenant soon.

11:26.018 --> 11:28.979
Yeah, yeah. I get it.
(SIGHS) That’s funny.

11:29.355 --> 11:32.149
I talked to a lady in the administration
at the last hospital Ed Miller worked.

11:32.650 --> 11:33.734
This is in Detroit.

11:34.026 --> 11:36.487
He was let go over personality issues,
she... she wouldn't elaborate

11:36.570 --> 11:39.240
but, apparently he bounced
from hospital to hospital.

11:39.323 --> 11:42.451
And she also said that Miller used to be
a prominent sexologist in the ’60s.

11:42.785 --> 11:46.789
Sexologist? You... you mean like sex,
like an expert on sex or something?

11:46.872 --> 11:48.999
-Easy there, killer.
-I’m just asking.

11:54.630 --> 11:55.631
Where you off to?

11:56.549 --> 11:59.719
Oh, uh, we contacTed
the Street Embrace organization.

11:59.885 --> 12:01.762
It’s run out of this
self-awareness fellowship place.

12:01.971 --> 12:04.932
a description of one of the girls
who participaTed, Zoe Prentice,

12:05.057 --> 12:07.852
matches what we got from a witness.
So, we are heading over there now.

12:07.977 --> 12:09.145
I’ll need to know these things.

12:09.687 --> 12:11.647
-Sorry, you were on the phone.
-Interrupt me next time.

12:11.814 --> 12:13.733
-Sure.
-(POLICE SIREN WAILING)

12:13.816 --> 12:15.067
-Sorry.
-No problem.

12:15.192 --> 12:16.402
(TELEPHONE RINGING)

12:16.777 --> 12:18.654
JOHN: 15th squad. Hi.
LAURA: Hey.

12:19.697 --> 12:20.906
Eric Pregitzer’s on his way up.

12:21.282 --> 12:22.283
(SIGHS)

12:22.366 --> 12:25.035
ANDY: No one at Miller’s hotel
saw him in the lobby bar.

12:25.244 --> 12:27.580
No one saw him walking through
the lobby with the woman.

12:27.997 --> 12:30.416
-Did you catch all that, Lieutenant?
-I did. Thank you.

12:30.583 --> 12:32.251
I ran Eric’s address, check that out.

12:34.128 --> 12:35.796
(TELEPHONE RINGING)

12:40.134 --> 12:43.637
Eric, uh, we wanTed to talk to you
about Dr. Ed Miller.

12:44.638 --> 12:47.349
My dad told me to talk to you guys,
tell me what happened.

12:47.725 --> 12:49.852
Yeah. Well, we saw on
Dr. Miller’s cellphone records

12:50.019 --> 12:51.896
that he had some calls into you yesterday.

12:52.188 --> 12:55.316
-What was he calling you about?
-Oh, suggestions and what to do

12:55.399 --> 12:57.735
in New York, you know,
he was out here by himself, so.

12:57.860 --> 13:00.613
Did you give him any suggestions
as far as places to go.

13:00.738 --> 13:02.198
You know, restaurants, bars, like that?

13:02.281 --> 13:06.869
No, more landmark-type stuff, you know.
The Met and Guggenheim.

13:06.952 --> 13:10.623
Hey Eric, in going through
some of the checklist things we do, uh,

13:10.873 --> 13:13.584
you know, we ran your address
to see if there were any crimes

13:13.667 --> 13:17.296
or police responses, you know.
It says here you tried to commit suicide

13:17.379 --> 13:18.422
three years ago.

13:19.215 --> 13:20.257
That’s right.

13:20.508 --> 13:24.220
Yeah, that’s a personal matter, obviously,
but what jumped out was

13:24.303 --> 13:26.889
that it was Dr. Miller who dialed 911.

13:27.348 --> 13:29.725
-That’s right.
-Was he staying with you?

13:29.892 --> 13:33.062
No, it was actually
kind of an ironic situation.

13:33.270 --> 13:38.859
I... I was going through a breakup,
and it was just a real low point for me.

13:38.943 --> 13:42.530
And so, I did something really stupid,
and Dr. Miller was in town,

13:42.613 --> 13:47.284
and he happened to stop by after I did it.
I’m glad he did ’cause it saved my life.

13:48.077 --> 13:49.370
See, that looks a little odd to us.

13:49.787 --> 13:53.999
No, I mean, yeah, I can see
how it maybe does, but it’s not.

13:54.124 --> 13:56.669
Eric, I’ve been doing this
for a long time and I’m pretty certain

13:56.752 --> 13:58.504
at this point
we’re not getting the whole story

13:58.629 --> 14:00.214
as to what you know about Dr. Miller.

14:03.509 --> 14:05.386
Are you thinking I killed him?

14:05.886 --> 14:08.472
Why in the world
would I do something like that?

14:09.557 --> 14:11.350
Were you more than just friends?

14:11.725 --> 14:15.479
Oh, my God.
You guys are really tripping now. No.

14:16.021 --> 14:19.817
Dr. Miller, uh, he was a lonely old guy
and didn’t know a lot of people.

14:19.900 --> 14:23.279
And he just kind of like
clung to my family for some reason.

14:23.612 --> 14:25.489
I... I don’t know what else to tell you.

14:26.073 --> 14:28.826
-Where were you last night?
-Work and then home.

14:29.410 --> 14:31.370
We’re gonna need your information,
if you don’t mind.

14:37.793 --> 14:39.211
RITA: So, the Street Embrace.

14:39.503 --> 14:43.132
Yeah. Oh, my God. What a great experience.

14:43.674 --> 14:45.426
You guys think we have it rough, right?

14:46.343 --> 14:50.472
In your travels the last few days,
did you come across a young homeless guy

14:50.556 --> 14:52.933
named Sean O'Leary?
His street name was The Illness.

14:53.434 --> 14:55.102
Yeah, yeah, I talked to him a little bit.

14:55.436 --> 14:57.104
He was gonna leave
for San Francisco today.

14:57.354 --> 15:00.357
Well, that’s not gonna happen.
Sean was shot and killed last night.

15:01.150 --> 15:02.985
-For real?
-Yeah.

